page.title: 09WILDLIFE AT WOODHALL
page.content: Quite a lot of species of birds were seen at Woodhall starting off with Swifts.The Swifts come to Britain for the summer like the Swallows.And the River Wharfe has enough insects to keep the Swifts hunger down.The Swifts feed in the air and hardley ever land. Willow Warbles could be heard and at one time could be seen darting across the river,skimming the surface.Outside the wood a cuckoo could be heard only in the far distance.A lot of Rooks were about,their nests were in the tall trees beside the river.The type of woodland was deciduous,and is great for birds like Tree Creepers,and,Blue, Great ,and Coal Tits.The fox population has decreased rapidly over the past ten years and foxes are very rare at Woodhall.The River Wharfe has many plants like plant weed.
